## Summary

`src/auth/encryption.ts` uses `crypto.pbkdf2Sync` with 100,000 iterations for key derivation. This blocks the Node.js event loop for ~50–100 ms per call. Since key encryption/decryption is triggered on community creation, identity operations, and repo signing, this creates measurable latency spikes under load.

Under a sustained rate of parallel identity operations (e.g., many simultaneous registrations), this can be weaponised as a **DoS amplifier**.

## Affected File

`src/auth/encryption.ts` (line 12)

```ts
function deriveKey(secret: string, salt: Buffer): Buffer {
  return crypto.pbkdf2Sync(secret, salt, ITERATIONS, KEY_LENGTH, 'sha512');
}
```

## Recommended Fix

```ts
import { promisify } from 'util';
const pbkdf2 = promisify(crypto.pbkdf2);
async function deriveKey(secret: string, salt: Buffer): Promise<Buffer> {
  return pbkdf2(secret, salt, ITERATIONS, KEY_LENGTH, 'sha512');
}
```

Make `encryptKeyBytes` and `decryptKeyBytes` `async` — they are already called from async contexts.

## Severity
🟠 **High** — event loop blocking under load; potential DoS amplifier.

## Summary

`src/oauth/external-routes.ts` stores OAuth callback pending-codes in an unbounded in-memory `Map`:

```ts
const pendingCodes = new Map<string, { tokens: LocalTokens; expiresAt: number }>();
```

The per-IP rate limiter (30 initiations / 15 min) only limits a single IP. An attacker with rotating IPs can create tens of thousands of entries. Each entry holds a full token payload. While codes expire after 60 seconds, a sustained attack with enough IPs can exhaust available heap memory.

## Recommended Fix

Cap the Map at a sane maximum (e.g., 10,000 entries) and evict the oldest entry on insert when at capacity:

```ts
const MAX_PENDING_CODES = 10_000;

function addPendingCode(code: string, entry: { tokens: LocalTokens; expiresAt: number }): void {
  if (pendingCodes.size >= MAX_PENDING_CODES) {
    const first = pendingCodes.keys().next().value;
    if (first) pendingCodes.delete(first);
  }
  pendingCodes.set(code, entry);
}
```

## Severity
🟠 **High** — memory exhaustion / denial of service.

## Summary

The SSRF guard (`isPrivateHost`) in `src/federation/remote-verify.ts` protects `resolveDidToPds` and `fetchRemoteRecord`, but the **peer health check** in `src/federation/peer-cache.ts` fetches `{peerUrl}/health` without validating the peer hostname through the SSRF guard.

A malicious `PEER_PDS_URLS` entry (or a future admin API to add peers) could cause the server to make HTTP requests to internal services.

## Affected File

`src/federation/peer-cache.ts` — peer health fetch

## Recommended Fix

Export `isPrivateHost` from `remote-verify.ts` and call it before fetching any peer URL:

```ts
import { isPrivateHost } from './remote-verify.js';

const peerHostname = new URL(peerUrl).hostname;
if (isPrivateHost(peerHostname)) {
  console.warn(`Skipping peer ${peerUrl}: private/internal host`);
  continue;
}
```

## Severity
🟡 **Medium** — SSRF risk via peer URL configuration.

## Summary

The `claim` field in `net.openfederation.community.issueAttestation` accepts **arbitrary nested JSON objects** with no depth limit or per-field size check. While the global 256 KB body limit provides an outer cap, a deeply-nested or maliciously crafted claim object could:
- Cause unbounded recursion in any serialiser/traverser that processes it
- Embed proto-XSS payloads that web UIs might render without sanitisation
- Inflate storage in `records_index` with large JSONB values

## Affected File

`src/api/net.openfederation.community.issueAttestation.ts`

## Recommended Fix

```ts
const MAX_CLAIM_SIZE = 4096; // 4 KB
const claimJson = JSON.stringify(claim);
if (claimJson.length > MAX_CLAIM_SIZE) {
  return res.status(400).json({
    error: 'PayloadTooLarge',
    message: `claim must not exceed ${MAX_CLAIM_SIZE} bytes when serialised`,
  });
}
```

## Severity
🟡 **Medium** — storage inflation; potential XSS via downstream rendering.
